One of Donald Trump=E2=80=99s most quoted campaign
promises was to launch, on day one, =E2=80=9Cthe largest deportation progra=
m of criminals in the history of America.=E2=80=9D But, perhaps needless to=
 say, he=E2=80=99s not going to be able to kick millions of illegal immigra=
nts out of the country on January 20. Actually removing people is the hypot=
hetical end point of what will inevitably be a dragged-out, vociferous, pol=
itically fraught, and logistically complex process involving warrants, iden=
tification, surveillance, detention, and many, many
lawyers. It=E2=80=99s an enormous=E2=80=94and enormously expensive=E2=80=94=
undertaking.

=C2=A0

But if Trump does attempt to implement his feverish campaign promise, how w=
ill he go about it? To get a candid perspective, I spoke with Ken Cuccinell=
i, a former Virginia attorney general and Trump=E2=80=99s former acting num=
ber two at the Department of Homeland Security. Cuccinelli admitted that so=
me of Trump=E2=80=99s rhetoric is hyperbolic, and
warned against expecting a mass raid or roundup to commence six days from n=
ow. But he still thinks there=E2=80=99s a lot Trump can do=E2=80=94and that=
 he already laid much of the groundwork in his first term. The following co=
nversation, lightly edited and condensed, has been excerpted from my podcas=
t, Somebody=E2=80=99s Gotta Win.=C2=A0=C2=A0

Day One
-------

Tara Palmeri: What do you think
about the possibility of Trump holding back support for California and its =
relief efforts once he=E2=80=99s sworn in, because it=E2=80=99s considered =
a sanctuary state and likely to push back on efforts to deport undocumented=
 immigrants?

=C2=A0

Ken Cuccinelli: I don=E2=80=99t think there=E2=80=99s ever a legitimate bas=
is for any state or locality not to at least be cooperative. They don=E2=80=
=99t have to offer their
own people and resources, but they need to at least cooperate in letting th=
e federal government accomplish its role in immigration law. I also don=E2=
=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s appropriate to make emergency support decisions =
based on other issues that are going on. I think both sides in that discuss=
ion are off-base to a certain extent. I=E2=80=99d rather there wasn=E2=80=
=99t crossover on these things. But let=E2=80=99s face it, President Donald=
 Trump writes his own rule book on these things. And sometimes that works t=
o the advantage of
people like Gavin Newsom; it did during Covid. And sometimes it does not, a=
s it appears right now with respect to the wildfires.

=C2=A0

Donald Trump was specific when he said on day one, he=E2=80=99s going to co=
nduct the largest deportation of all time. Do you think that=E2=80=99s poss=
ible?

=C2=A0

What will
happen to implement that commitment is that all of the presidential instruc=
tions that are necessary to commence large-scale deportation will be signed=
 on day one. Does that mean 5,000 ICE agents are suddenly going to deport 1=
0 million people in one day? No, it doesn=E2=80=99t mean that. But it does =
mean the presidential authority to commence that effort will begin on day o=
ne. Will there be refinements after day one? Absolutely.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Do you think there will be any activity on day one besides the order?

=C2=A0

The key activity will be at the border itself. So yes, there will be actual=
 activity on day one, but the activity will be the first steps=E2=80=94actu=
al steps, not just orders=E2=80=94of sealing the border. And by sealing the=
 border, I mean [sealing it] to illegal traffic, particularly
between the legal ports of entry. We have a nearly 2,000-mile border with M=
exico, and, of course, only a few points of legal entry into the United Sta=
tes.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That doesn=E2=80=99t mean it will be closed on day one, but you=E2=80=99ll =
see actual deployment of individuals. From the moment Donald Trump is sworn=
 in as president, border patrol goes from 20,000 greeters who are executing=
 a catch-and-release plan, by and
large=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s been reduced a bit the last few months=E2=80=
=94to actual enforcers of the border.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Who are these people who will be securing the border? Existing Border Patro=
l agents who are sitting on the sidelines? Or the military? I mean, you nee=
d money for people to go to the border and actually seal it off=E2=80=A6

=C2=A0

You don=E2=80=99t need money for the Border Patrol agents, because you=E2=
=80=99ve already budgeted it, and now you=E2=80=99re just cutting them loos=
e to actually perform the mission of the Border Patrol, which is to patrol =
the border instead of being greeters, as I refer to them. That=E2=80=99s a =
very dramatic change. You go from 20,000 helping people in, to 20,000 keepi=
ng people out=E2=80=94a 40,000-person swing with no change in the budget. I=
 also fully expect deployment of military members on the border very
quickly; I think some of the orders you see issued on day one will be to de=
ploy military members to the border between the legal ports of entry. And u=
nlike the first Trump administration, and the Biden administration, where t=
hey backed up the border patrol and provided reconnaissance but didn=E2=80=
=99t do any confronting of people entering the country, I think the militar=
y will be used in Trump=E2=80=99s second term to actually stop people from =
entering in the first place.

=C2=A0

Is it legal to use the military? Why didn=E2=80=99t Trump do it during the =
first term?

=C2=A0

The question of its legality isn=E2=80=99t, in my view, why it wasn=E2=80=
=99t utilized earlier; it was the reluctance to use the military. And, as y=
ou heard Donald Trump in the campaign, he is over that reluctance.

=C2=A0

Do you expect the courts to try to stop that=E2=80=94for example, a Califor=
nia injunction?

=C2=A0

They can=E2=80=99t stop that.

=C2=A0

They were able to stop the Muslim ban for a long time. Trump=E2=80=99s side=
 eventually won, but they were able to hold up a number of other
orders=E2=80=A6

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99s interesting that the second Trump term will benefit from a lot=
 of that litigation having already happened in the first Trump term. That=
=E2=80=99s the law of the land now. And the Muslim ban, as you referred to =
it=E2=80=94of course, it involved more countries than just Islamic countrie=
s, but that was the press name for it=E2=80=94was upheld. That=E2=80=99s be=
en litigated. And at the Supreme Court level, that=E2=80=99s an immigration=
 law
authority. When you deploy the military, that [falls under] the [Commander-=
in-Chief Clause] of Article II in the Constitution, which gives the preside=
nt authority to secure the country. He doesn=E2=80=99t have to let anybody =
in between the legal ports of entry, under any circumstances, and he can de=
ploy the military to stop the invasion.

Trains, Planes, and Automobiles
-------------------------------

Trump is saying he wants to remove 1 million to 2 million
people, adding to the 1.4 million who currently have orders for immediate r=
emoval. How do you do that? How much does that cost? It seems this is a mas=
sive hurdle, logistically.

=C2=A0

The logistics of this promise are massive. It=E2=80=99s the biggest logisti=
cal domestic undertaking of our lifetime, if they=E2=80=99re going to come =
close to meeting the advertised goals of this campaign promise. And that wi=
ll take a lot
of money. The price will vary by year, because once you=E2=80=99ve built th=
e infrastructure, your cost per deportation is going to start to go down. S=
o there=E2=80=99s going to be a bit of a spike early, and a drop later, on =
a per-deportation basis. My guess is that, across multiple years, you=E2=80=
=99re going to be talking $10 billion to $15 billion. The [incoming] Trump =
administration is asking for a lump sum upfront. But a big part of that is =
also to finish the wall. And when we say =E2=80=9Cthe wall,=E2=80=9D we=E2=
=80=99re talking about a
whole system, just to be clear.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

A lot of this will happen by cracking down on the issuance of work permits =
and the use of Homeland Security investigators to do vastly more workplace =
enforcement of immigration laws, which will not only put illegal aliens at =
risk, but also put their American employers at legal criminal risk. The rea=
lity that this is happening at scale will lead many employers to be a
lot more careful in making sure they=E2=80=99re complying with employment l=
aw, including the employment of people who are not here legally. Because so=
 many people come here to work, that will lead a large number of people to =
return home, because they won=E2=80=99t be able to work anymore.

=C2=A0

I spoke with an ICE agent who told me we have to make agreements with the c=
ountries to actually take their people back. What do
we do with people who are waiting for their asylum claims to be granted?

=C2=A0

Of course, the point of those proceedings is to reach a final order and the=
n to deport them. To deport about a million people a year is probably about=
 50 plane loads a day. The traditional way that deportations have worked is=
 the country you=E2=80=99re deporting someone back to knows they=E2=80=99re=
 coming, and has correctively agreed to
them coming by validating their citizenship. I think with a Trump presidenc=
y, you=E2=80=99ll see things start that way. With respect to Cuba, Venezuel=
a, and Nicaragua, there may be some cooperation. But don=E2=80=99t discount=
 the possibility that if President Donald Trump thinks any of these countri=
es are dragging their feet=E2=80=94he may not wait, or ask their permission=
=2E He may literally just give them the=
se people and drop them on their doors=
tep. With the kind of numbers we=E2=80=99re talking about, it=E2=80=99s har=
d for me to
imagine that not happening.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Trump has four years in office. What year will it be when ICE officers are =
knocking on doors and telling people to pack up and leave?

=C2=A0

Some of that will happen right off the bat, but they won=E2=80=99t be prior=
ities. If you=E2=80=99re going to pick up someone who has a
deportation order already, and they live with 10 other people who are here =
illegally, then, unlike the Biden administration, which ignored those 10 pe=
ople, the Trump 2.0 administration would immediately begin processing those=
 folks in an effort to achieve efficiency. The ones who are, for instance, =
under expedited removal authority will be removed immediately. So you will =
cross into some of those categories [of people] who don=E2=80=99t today hav=
e immediate removal orders and who haven=E2=80=99t committed
another crime. They may not be the targets, but they can easily be swept up=
 while those other targets are being picked up, whereas they=E2=80=99d prev=
iously been ignored while the targets alone were focused on.

=C2=A0

So some of them are on immediate removal, but for the most part, the first =
year is going to be people who are in prison or already detained. Do you as=
sume there will be more raids of farming or
hospitality centers?

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99m not prepared to describe the types of employers that would be t=
argeted, because it won=E2=80=99t be so much by type of employer, as it wil=
l be where the evidence leads to suggesting there are larger numbers of ill=
egals being employed. Again, I=E2=80=99m speaking of it from an efficiency =
standpoint, rather than a culpability standpoint. And if you=E2=80=99re Don=
ald Trump and you want to
get as high numbers as you can on actual deportation and actual removal, yo=
u=E2=80=99re going to focus on the more efficient approaches and locations =
first.

=C2=A0

Is he going to want to create a perception of force and get the media invol=
ved?

=C2=A0

I=E2=80=99m not so sure that=E2=80=99s correct. I think the key factor for =
deterrence is
the belief by all parties=E2=80=94employers and illegals=E2=80=94that this =
is going to happen on a determined, regular basis, and they=E2=80=99re goin=
g to follow through on it once they=E2=80=99ve begun. I don=E2=80=99t think=
 seeing it in the media is going to be particularly critical to that. It=E2=
=80=99s the reality of the occurrence of it. It=E2=80=99s the same thing th=
at deters someone in another country from attempting to come here in the fi=
rst place: their belief that they=E2=80=99re not going to get in. Are they =
going to spend their life savings and
give it to some coyote for a small percentage chance of getting into the co=
untry? Some will, but not many, and not at the numbers we=E2=80=99ve seen o=
ver the last 10 or 15 years.

=C2=A0

What do you think we=E2=80=99ll feel in the first 100 days in terms of immi=
gration?

=C2=A0

Well, I think it=E2=80=99s going to
feel fast. You=E2=80=99re going to see the quickest approach to 100 percent=
 of a campaign promise kept at the border, because it=E2=80=99s the fastest=
 place it can be kept, and because the president needs no additional author=
ity or funding to do it. That=E2=80=99s what you=E2=80=99ll see in the firs=
t 100 days as they begin to ramp up the largest deportation effort of our l=
ifetime.=C2=A0

