ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Trump is saying he wants to remove 1 mi=
llion to 2 million
people, adding to the 1.4 million who currently have orders for immediate r=
emoval. How do you do that? How much does that cost? It seems this is a mas=
sive hurdle, logistically.</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The logistics of th=
is promise are massive. It=E2=80=99s the biggest logistical domestic undert=
aking of our lifetime, if they=E2=80=99re going to come close to meeting th=
e advertised goals of this campaign promise. And that will take a lot
of money. The price will vary by year, because once you=E2=80=99ve built th=
e infrastructure, your cost per deportation is going to start to go down. S=
o there=E2=80=99s going to be a bit of a spike early, and a drop later, on =
a per-deportation basis. My guess is that, across multiple years, you=E2=80=
=99re going to be talking $10 billion to $15 billion. The [incoming] Trump =
administration is asking for a lump sum upfront. But a big part of that is =
also to finish the wall. And when we say =E2=80=9Cthe wall,=E2=80=9D we=E2=
=80=99re talking about a
whole system, just to be clear.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">A lot of this wil=
l happen by cracking down on the issuance of work permits and the use of Ho=
meland Security investigators to do vastly more workplace enforcement of im=
migration laws, which will not only put illegal aliens at risk, but also pu=
t their American employers at legal criminal risk. The reality that this is=
 happening at scale will lead many employers to be a
lot more careful in making sure they=E2=80=99re complying with employment l=
aw, including the employment of people who are not here legally. Because so=
 many people come here to work, that will lead a large number of people to =
return home, because they won=E2=80=99t be able to work anymore.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;"><strong>I spoke with an ICE agent who told me we have to make agr=
eements with the countries to actually take their people back. What do
we do with people who are waiting for their asylum claims to be granted?</s=
trong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, the point of those proceedings is to =
reach a final order and then to deport them. To deport about a million peop=
le a year is probably about 50 plane loads a day. The traditional way that =
deportations have worked is the country you=E2=80=99re deporting someone ba=
ck to knows they=E2=80=99re coming, and has correctively agreed to
them coming by validating their citizenship. I think with a Trump presidenc=
y, you=E2=80=99ll see things start that way. With respect to Cuba, Venezuel=
a, and Nicaragua, there may be some cooperation. But don=E2=80=99t discount=
 the possibility that if President Donald Trump thinks any of these countri=
es are dragging their feet=E2=80=94he may not wait, or ask their permission=
=2E He may literally just give them the=
se people and drop them on their doors=
tep. With the kind of numbers we=E2=80=99re talking about, it=E2=80=99s har=
d for me to
imagine that <em>not </em>happening.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Trum=
p has four years in office. What year will it be when ICE officers are knoc=
king on doors and telling people to pack up and leave?</strong></p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Some of that will happen right off the bat, but they won=E2=80=99t=
 be priorities. If you=E2=80=99re going to pick up someone who has a
deportation order already, and they live with 10 other people who are here =
illegally, then, unlike the Biden administration, which ignored those 10 pe=
ople, the Trump 2.0 administration would immediately begin processing those=
 folks in an effort to achieve efficiency. The ones who are, for instance, =
under expedited removal authority will be removed immediately. So you will =
cross into some of those categories [of people] who don=E2=80=99t today hav=
e immediate removal orders and who haven=E2=80=99t committed
another crime. They may not be the targets, but they can easily be swept up=
 while those other targets are being picked up, whereas they=E2=80=99d prev=
iously been ignored while the targets alone were focused on.</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;"><strong>So some of them are on immediate removal, but for the most pa=
rt, the first year is going to be people who are in prison or already detai=
ned. Do you assume there will be more raids of farming or
hospitality centers?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=80=99m not prepared=
 to describe the types of employers that would be targeted, because it won=
=E2=80=99t be so much by <em>type</em> of employer, as it will be where the=
 evidence leads to suggesting there are larger numbers of illegals being em=
ployed. Again, I=E2=80=99m speaking of it from an efficiency standpoint, ra=
ther than a culpability standpoint. And if you=E2=80=99re Donald Trump and =
you want to
get as high numbers as you can on actual deportation and actual removal, yo=
u=E2=80=99re going to focus on the more efficient approaches and locations =
first.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Is he going to want to create a percepti=
on of force and get the media involved?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=E2=
=80=99m not so sure that=E2=80=99s correct. I think the key factor for dete=
rrence is
the belief by all parties=E2=80=94employers and illegals=E2=80=94that this =
is going to happen on a determined, regular basis, and they=E2=80=99re goin=
g to follow through on it once they=E2=80=99ve begun. I don=E2=80=99t think=
 seeing it in the media is going to be particularly critical to that. It=E2=
=80=99s the reality of the occurrence of it. It=E2=80=99s the same thing th=
at deters someone in another country from attempting to come here in the fi=
rst place: their belief that they=E2=80=99re not going to get in. Are they =
going to spend their life savings and
give it to some coyote for a small percentage chance of getting into the co=
untry? Some will, but not many, and not at the numbers we=E2=80=99ve seen o=
ver the last 10 or 15 years.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>What do you thin=
k we=E2=80=99ll </strong><strong><em>feel</em></strong><strong> in the firs=
t 100 days in terms of immigration?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Well, I think it=E2=80=99s g=
oing to
feel fast. You=E2=80=99re going to see the quickest approach to 100 percent=
 of a campaign promise kept at the border, because it=E2=80=99s the fastest=
 place it can be kept, and because the president needs no additional author=
ity or funding to do it. That=E2=80=99s what you=E2=80=99ll see in the firs=
t 100 days as they begin to ramp up the largest deportation effort of our l=
ifetime.=C2=A0</p></div>
